1
00:02:29,426 --> 00:02:32,486
<i>It has come down to this.
Eight seconds to go.</i>

2
00:02:32,696 --> 00:02:35,358
One possession.
Marv Albert with Bill Walton...

3
00:02:35,432 --> 00:02:38,492
...from the America West Arena
in Phoenix, Arizona.

4
00:02:38,635 --> 00:02:41,195
l can't hear myself over the crowd.

5
00:02:41,304 --> 00:02:44,296
<i>If the Suns win they go to the finals.
If they lose...</i>

6
00:02:44,841 --> 00:02:46,968
...they go back to San Antonio.

7
00:02:47,044 --> 00:02:48,306
We got eight seconds.

8
00:02:48,445 --> 00:02:50,276
Lots of time for the straight line.

9
00:02:50,380 --> 00:02:54,510
Majerle, take the ball, get it to KJ,
and get through.

10
00:02:54,785 --> 00:02:57,276
Kick it back to Chuck. And Chuck...

11
00:02:57,554 --> 00:02:59,852
- ...you win the game.
- Get me the ball.

12
00:03:00,524 --> 00:03:02,458
No time outs left. Let's go.

13
00:03:02,526 --> 00:03:03,458
Suns!

14
00:03:03,627 --> 00:03:06,152
<i>This is what it's all about,
game-winning time.</i>

15
00:03:06,229 --> 00:03:09,721
<i>- I'm looking for Barkley to step up.
- What a shock!</i>

16
00:03:10,133 --> 00:03:13,296
<i>For those who just tuned in,
Robinson fouled out.</i>

17
00:03:13,904 --> 00:03:17,203
<i>For the Admiral, 43 points, 21 rebounds.</i>

18
00:03:17,941 --> 00:03:19,499
<i>Here we go. Dan Majerle...</i>

19
00:03:19,576 --> 00:03:21,271
<i>...will inbound the basketball.</i>

20
00:03:21,344 --> 00:03:25,337
<i>The Suns, one possession from elimination.
They're going wild.</i>

21
00:03:26,817 --> 00:03:29,149
<i>Kevin Johnson takes it, moves to the right.</i>

22
00:03:29,219 --> 00:03:31,585
<i>Johnson setting it up, looking for Barkley.</i>

23
00:03:31,888 --> 00:03:33,378
<i>We're down to six.</i>

24
00:03:33,557 --> 00:03:35,252
<i>Barkley angles for the shot.</i>

25
00:03:35,892 --> 00:03:37,553
<i>Barkley, to his left.</i>

26
00:03:37,627 --> 00:03:39,117
<i>Barkley, checking the clock.</i>

27
00:03:39,362 --> 00:03:41,227
<i>Barkley, with the release.</i>

28
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:47,996
<i>It's all over. Charles Barkley has put
the Phoenix Suns in the NBA finals.</i>

29
00:03:49,039 --> 00:03:50,734
<i>The most dramatic victory...</i>

30
00:03:50,841 --> 00:03:53,969
<i>...in the history in the Suns' franchise.</i>

31
00:03:57,681 --> 00:04:01,242
No basket! The shot was after the buzzer.
Game's over.

32
00:04:01,518 --> 00:04:04,180
- Are you crazy?
- No! Charles, you didn't get it off.

33
00:04:04,688 --> 00:04:06,121
- Bullshit.
- You were late.

34
00:04:06,189 --> 00:04:07,349
He was late.

35
00:04:07,424 --> 00:04:08,413
He got it off!

36
00:04:08,492 --> 00:04:09,322
He didn't.

37
00:04:13,063 --> 00:04:15,327
- You're wrong!
- You didn't get it off!

38
00:04:15,398 --> 00:04:18,390
- That is total bullshit.
- Watch yourself, Charles.

39
00:04:18,568 --> 00:04:21,230
- You were late.
- Jack called it good. Ask for help.

40
00:04:21,371 --> 00:04:24,033
l don't need any help. You didn't get it off!

41
00:04:24,107 --> 00:04:25,438
Bullshit.

42
00:04:25,709 --> 00:04:27,973
You want to play next game?
Watch yourself.

43
00:04:28,044 --> 00:04:29,534
You suck. You suck.

44
00:04:29,713 --> 00:04:32,705
Watch yourself. No basket. Game's over.

45
00:04:32,883 --> 00:04:35,181
l don't want to protect you, but l must.

46
00:04:35,352 --> 00:04:37,013
Bullshit! Bullshit!

47
00:04:40,757 --> 00:04:44,659
The crowd appears to be voicing
its displeasure.

48
00:04:45,162 --> 00:04:46,993
Hey, Charles!

49
00:04:47,564 --> 00:04:49,759
l'll see you in San Antonio.

50
00:04:49,833 --> 00:04:52,165
You'll see me kick your ass!

51
00:04:53,637 --> 00:04:55,901
l wouldn't want
to be Mickey Gordon tonight...

52
00:04:55,972 --> 00:04:58,998
...or any other night
the rest of my life here in Phoenix.

53
00:04:59,176 --> 00:05:01,508
l hope you die!

54
00:05:01,678 --> 00:05:02,576
Need help?

55
00:05:02,646 --> 00:05:05,012
- l saw it. He was late.
- Let's get you out.

56
00:05:05,148 --> 00:05:06,479
This isn't my jacket.

57
00:05:06,850 --> 00:05:09,114
Screw your jacket. Let's go.

58
00:05:09,186 --> 00:05:13,850
<i>As Mickey Gordon leaves, you can only
think that as long as they play basketball...</i>

59
00:05:14,224 --> 00:05:17,284
<i>...they'll talk about that controversial call.</i>

60
00:05:17,360 --> 00:05:19,760
<i>For Bill Walton, I'm Marv Albert.</i>

61
00:05:20,564 --> 00:05:24,227
<i>As a sports writer for 20 years,
I've covered every great event there is.</i>

62
00:05:24,301 --> 00:05:27,566
<i>And I'm watching my best friend
make the gutsiest call...</i>

63
00:05:27,704 --> 00:05:29,797
<i>...in the history of basketball.</i>

64
00:05:30,140 --> 00:05:32,938
<i>Every news show in America ran it
for two days.</i>

65
00:05:33,009 --> 00:05:36,445
<i>Don't sit Gordon and Barkley together
at a dinner party.</i>

66
00:05:36,513 --> 00:05:38,811
<i>The sports world is still stunned...</i>

67
00:05:38,882 --> 00:05:40,645
<i>...by this controversial call.</i>

68
00:05:40,717 --> 00:05:45,450
<i>Gordon remains in seclusion
under police guard. But bravo, Mickey!</i>

69
00:05:45,555 --> 00:05:49,457
<i>We need such leadership
and decision-making in the White House.</i>

70
00:05:51,094 --> 00:05:54,257
<i>No news, no weather,
no theatre reviews, just that...</i>

71
00:05:54,364 --> 00:05:57,197
...over and over again.
And you know what?

72
00:05:57,400 --> 00:06:00,892
Mickey got it right.
Right there, live on the spot.

73
00:06:01,071 --> 00:06:02,163
He got it right.

74
00:06:02,239 --> 00:06:05,174
The shot was late
by a hundredth of a second.

75
00:06:05,242 --> 00:06:06,402
Oh, God.

76
00:06:07,544 --> 00:06:09,808
Honey, that's an amazing story.

77
00:06:10,046 --> 00:06:13,482
lf only l liked basketball,
I’d have really liked it.

78
00:06:13,650 --> 00:06:15,311
I’m kidding.

79
00:06:15,485 --> 00:06:17,578
Welcome to Helen's. Something to drink?

80
00:06:17,687 --> 00:06:22,454
- Champagne, when the others arrive.
- We're getting married.

81
00:06:23,059 --> 00:06:24,185
Fine with me.

82
00:06:24,861 --> 00:06:26,089
How's the house wine?

83
00:06:26,329 --> 00:06:29,025
lt's like me: fruity, yet oddly appealing.

84
00:06:29,566 --> 00:06:31,158
We'll wait.

85
00:06:31,568 --> 00:06:33,536
He'll wait. l'll have a glass of red.

86
00:06:33,837 --> 00:06:35,236
You got it.

87
00:06:36,306 --> 00:06:39,036
- I’m a little nervous, all right?
- About what?

88
00:06:39,209 --> 00:06:40,938
Meeting your friends.

89
00:06:41,344 --> 00:06:45,246
They're flying in to New York
from all over the country...

90
00:06:45,515 --> 00:06:46,948
...to look at me.

91
00:06:47,083 --> 00:06:48,744
l'll feel like a show horse.

92
00:06:48,952 --> 00:06:52,353
They'll love you.
Craig and Lucy were wild for you.

93
00:06:53,757 --> 00:06:56,453
Mickey's great. l can't wait
for you to meet him.

94
00:06:56,860 --> 00:06:58,919
l tell you, it's unbelievable.

95
00:06:59,262 --> 00:07:03,323
Three months ago, I’m this confirmed
single dope living in New York...

96
00:07:03,400 --> 00:07:07,336
...writing for the paper l delivered as a kid,
and l get your fax.

97
00:07:07,504 --> 00:07:09,267
One little number off.

98
00:07:09,606 --> 00:07:12,268
- And, bing! We both are--
- l know.

99
00:07:12,475 --> 00:07:15,774
Then l started faxing you
and you start faxing me.

100
00:07:15,979 --> 00:07:18,106
Then pretty soon we're just...

101
00:07:18,214 --> 00:07:20,011
...faxing each other's brains out.

102
00:07:23,119 --> 00:07:24,017
House red.

103
00:07:24,421 --> 00:07:25,251
Thanks.

104
00:07:25,355 --> 00:07:29,553
lt must be the strangest way for
two people to get together l ever heard of.

105
00:07:30,660 --> 00:07:31,649
No.

106
00:07:33,129 --> 00:07:36,792
Mickey and Ellen hold the title
for the strangest getting together.

107
00:07:36,866 --> 00:07:38,561
At least in their weight class.

108
00:07:38,635 --> 00:07:40,102
How did they get together?

109
00:07:40,804 --> 00:07:42,396
She helped bury his father.

110
00:07:44,107 --> 00:07:45,096
Excuse me?

111
00:07:46,309 --> 00:07:48,709
No. l'll wait for Mickey to tell that story.

112
00:07:50,046 --> 00:07:51,946
Wait. Are you crazy?

113
00:07:52,315 --> 00:07:56,877
You can't start a story, ''She helped bury
his father'' and stop. lt's not allowed.

114
00:07:57,120 --> 00:08:00,385
- Come on.
- All right, all right. Here we go.

115
00:08:00,824 --> 00:08:02,291
This was a few years ago.

116
00:08:03,593 --> 00:08:05,083
Mickey's father died.

117
00:08:05,428 --> 00:08:07,157
lt's good. Mickey hated him.

118
00:08:07,430 --> 00:08:08,158
What?

119
00:08:08,231 --> 00:08:11,462
Everybody did. He left his family
when Mickey was a kid.

120
00:08:11,935 --> 00:08:14,768
When he left,
the neighbourhood had a street fair.

121
00:08:14,904 --> 00:08:17,202
l won a fishing rod.
Best time we ever had.

122
00:08:17,941 --> 00:08:20,000
Anyway, he dies...

123
00:08:20,143 --> 00:08:21,235
...finally.

124
00:08:21,611 --> 00:08:25,012
And the funeral service is
in the cargo area at JFK.

125
00:08:25,348 --> 00:08:26,337
<i>Why?</i>

126
00:08:26,649 --> 00:08:28,640
<i>He wants to be buried in France.</i>

127
00:08:28,718 --> 00:08:31,448
<i>- Was he French?
- No. He was in the D-day invasion.</i>

128
00:08:31,755 --> 00:08:34,417
<i>I think on our side, but I'm not sure.</i>

129
00:08:34,657 --> 00:08:38,252
<i>His whole platoon, except him,
was wiped out defending a village.</i>

130
00:08:38,328 --> 00:08:41,388
<i>They were buried there and he wanted
to be buried with them.</i>

131
00:08:41,631 --> 00:08:43,223
<i>That's sweet.</i>

132
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:44,765
<i>Okay.</i>

133
00:08:45,402 --> 00:08:49,930
<i>So, Mickey has to go over and accompany
the body, and see that it gets buried.</i>

134
00:08:50,473 --> 00:08:52,464
<i>Why, if he was such a bad guy?</i>

135
00:08:52,642 --> 00:08:57,136
<i>Whatever his father had done to him,
Mickey wanted to have a clear conscience.</i>

136
00:08:58,014 --> 00:08:59,481
<i>That's Mickey.</i>

137
00:09:00,316 --> 00:09:03,251
<i>Then there was this little problem.</i>

138
00:09:03,586 --> 00:09:05,315
You lost my father?

139
00:09:06,089 --> 00:09:07,078
<i>Oui.</i>

140
00:09:07,223 --> 00:09:09,748
We're not talking about a Valpac here.

141
00:09:09,993 --> 00:09:14,453
We're talking about a former person
in a bad suit in a big wooden box...

142
00:09:14,531 --> 00:09:16,829
<i>...and all you can say to me is ''oui''?</i>

143
00:09:18,601 --> 00:09:22,128
<i>He's going crazy,
but he's trying not to go off on anyone.</i>

144
00:09:22,305 --> 00:09:26,469
<i>This guy argues for a living.
He'd tell Shaquille O'Neal to shut up.</i>

145
00:09:26,743 --> 00:09:28,973
<i>He doesn't want to be the Ugly American.</i>

146
00:09:29,045 --> 00:09:30,740
Can l see your superior?

147
00:09:31,448 --> 00:09:32,472
Please...

148
00:09:32,816 --> 00:09:37,276
l know you're all angry over Euro Disney,
but don't take it out on me.

149
00:09:39,489 --> 00:09:40,547
Okay.

150
00:09:41,891 --> 00:09:44,826
Whatever you do,
l am not going to lose my temper.

151
00:09:45,361 --> 00:09:46,385
<i>Finally...</i>

152
00:09:46,463 --> 00:09:48,931
lf l was Hitler, you'd give me my father.

153
00:09:49,165 --> 00:09:53,067
You'd give me everything
in your goddamn country. Where is he?

154
00:09:54,637 --> 00:09:56,070
<i>Two days.</i>

155
00:09:56,840 --> 00:09:58,273
<i>Two days?</i>

156
00:09:58,341 --> 00:10:01,174
<i>He was in that airport two days.</i>

157
00:10:05,448 --> 00:10:06,779
<i>Monsieur Gordon...</i>

158
00:10:07,150 --> 00:10:09,050
Will you come with me, please?

159
00:10:10,553 --> 00:10:12,248
<i>But the airline was nice.</i>

160
00:10:12,622 --> 00:10:14,180
<i>They gave him free almonds.</i>

161
00:10:22,866 --> 00:10:24,595
<i>Where does Ellen come in?</i>

162
00:10:25,068 --> 00:10:26,126
<i>Now.</i>

163
00:10:42,352 --> 00:10:43,319
Mr. Gordon...

164
00:10:43,553 --> 00:10:45,043
...I’m Miss Andrews.

165
00:10:45,488 --> 00:10:47,353
Would you come into my office?

166
00:10:53,997 --> 00:10:55,487
Please have a seat.

167
00:10:57,066 --> 00:10:58,897
How are you feeling today?

168
00:10:59,135 --> 00:11:02,104
How am l today? l am a mass of good will.

169
00:11:02,438 --> 00:11:04,167
- You're American.
- Yes.

170
00:11:04,340 --> 00:11:07,639
On behalf of the airline,
l apologize for any problem--

171
00:11:07,844 --> 00:11:10,335
Problem? There's no problem.

172
00:11:10,513 --> 00:11:12,947
You lost my father. My rear end's...

173
00:11:13,082 --> 00:11:15,516
...moulded to a plastic chair
and I’ve got gas...

174
00:11:15,685 --> 00:11:20,019
...from eating those almonds.
I’m so happy I’m a walking Mardi Gras.

175
00:11:20,423 --> 00:11:21,720
That's funny.

176
00:11:21,858 --> 00:11:25,350
You have a delightfully sharp way
of expressing yourself.

177
00:11:25,962 --> 00:11:28,396
A terrible thing has been done to you...

178
00:11:28,498 --> 00:11:32,730
...and we really are sorry.
You've every right to insult, belittle...

179
00:11:32,869 --> 00:11:35,394
...and abuse the staff
who have tried to help you.

180
00:11:35,738 --> 00:11:37,069
ln fact, we thank you.

181
00:11:37,140 --> 00:11:40,405
And we voted you Traveller of the Month,
so congratulations.

182
00:11:42,245 --> 00:11:44,042
Anything else you'd like to say?

183
00:11:45,348 --> 00:11:46,940
No, l think that's it.

184
00:11:47,350 --> 00:11:50,114
Good. We found your father.

185
00:11:50,220 --> 00:11:53,485
The coffin landed here,
but evidently it was mis-tagged.

186
00:11:53,623 --> 00:11:56,251
- You should always tip more at the curb.
- Definitely.

187
00:11:56,326 --> 00:11:59,489
- lt accidentally was sent to Switzerland.
- Switzerland?

188
00:11:59,562 --> 00:12:01,792
- We had trouble with them.
- They're vicious.

189
00:12:01,998 --> 00:12:05,900
- They punched holes in my cheese.
- l thought they were neutral.

190
00:12:06,069 --> 00:12:09,368
They held your father in quarantine
for health reasons.

191
00:12:09,439 --> 00:12:13,773
Health reasons? He's dead.
He has no health. He's been de-healthed.

192
00:12:22,585 --> 00:12:25,577
There he is. Okay? Let's get out of here.

193
00:12:25,755 --> 00:12:26,813
Well...

194
00:12:29,259 --> 00:12:30,851
Do you have the claim checks?

195
00:12:30,927 --> 00:12:31,916
Why?

196
00:12:32,095 --> 00:12:37,032
Are there two of these that look alike?
My coffin has red yarn on the handle.

197
00:12:38,401 --> 00:12:40,392
What are you doing?

198
00:12:40,603 --> 00:12:42,798
We must make sure
that this is your father.

199
00:12:43,106 --> 00:12:47,839
lf it's a mad little guy giving you the finger,
it's him. Don't make me look.

200
00:12:49,112 --> 00:12:52,741
Sorry, but with all the confusion
l need you to identify him.

201
00:12:54,017 --> 00:12:57,646
Then put him on his stomach,
because I’m used to seeing him walk away.

202
00:12:58,454 --> 00:12:59,716
Right.

203
00:13:00,456 --> 00:13:01,480
Okay?

204
00:13:01,791 --> 00:13:02,951
Okay.

205
00:13:03,526 --> 00:13:06,791
That's enough. It'll be fine. Come on.

206
00:13:18,641 --> 00:13:19,630
Waiter?

207
00:13:21,644 --> 00:13:22,838
That looks good.

208
00:13:26,482 --> 00:13:27,813
Are you alone?

209
00:13:27,884 --> 00:13:30,079
Alone? l don't even have silverware.

210
00:13:30,219 --> 00:13:32,312
- Sit down.
- Thanks.

211
00:13:32,789 --> 00:13:35,053
What exactly is that?

212
00:13:35,558 --> 00:13:36,547
This?

213
00:13:36,659 --> 00:13:37,990
l don't know.

214
00:13:38,494 --> 00:13:41,861
l thought l ordered a martini,
but they brought me a backyard.

215
00:13:42,632 --> 00:13:45,032
Are you hungry?
Can l order you the wrong thing?

216
00:13:45,101 --> 00:13:47,569
No, thank you, I’m on my way out.

217
00:13:47,637 --> 00:13:49,901
Yeah, l noticed. Auto show?

218
00:13:50,373 --> 00:13:53,035
No, actually I’m going to the opera.

219
00:13:53,676 --> 00:13:56,201
Don't leave until the fat lady sings.

220
00:13:57,513 --> 00:13:59,174
No, l never do.

221
00:13:59,882 --> 00:14:01,873
Waiter, please, this is--

222
00:14:04,120 --> 00:14:05,951
lt's a loaner. l had no jacket.

223
00:14:06,322 --> 00:14:07,949
Right. l guessed.

224
00:14:08,224 --> 00:14:12,285
lt's a good look for me, don't you think?
Sort of the Ellis lsland Collection?

225
00:14:12,695 --> 00:14:13,753
lt's you.

226
00:14:13,930 --> 00:14:15,693
And l don't even know you.

227
00:14:17,333 --> 00:14:22,270
l really have to go. l wanted to tell you
that everything is taken care of.

228
00:14:22,672 --> 00:14:24,799
We'll deliver the casket to the cemetery.

229
00:14:24,874 --> 00:14:26,569
A car'll pick you up at 8:00...

230
00:14:26,642 --> 00:14:28,576
...and bring you back to the airport.

231
00:14:28,644 --> 00:14:31,636
We've upgraded your ticket to first class.

232
00:14:31,981 --> 00:14:34,176
And the ticket is free both ways.

233
00:14:34,617 --> 00:14:37,051
That's supposed to make up
for losing my father?

234
00:14:37,220 --> 00:14:39,051
We'll also pay your hotel bill.

235
00:14:39,222 --> 00:14:40,655
Yes!

236
00:14:43,893 --> 00:14:46,726
Well, l'll leave you in your grief.

237
00:14:47,263 --> 00:14:50,130
Will anyone else need transportation
to the cemetery?

238
00:14:50,199 --> 00:14:52,531
No. l will be the only one there.

239
00:14:53,169 --> 00:14:54,397
Oh, how sad.

240
00:14:54,570 --> 00:14:56,435
Good, 'cause it's a funeral.

241
00:14:57,173 --> 00:14:58,162
Right.

242
00:14:59,876 --> 00:15:00,808
'Bye-bye.

243
00:15:02,478 --> 00:15:04,241
Miss Andrews...

244
00:15:08,317 --> 00:15:10,080
l just wanted to thank you...

245
00:15:10,253 --> 00:15:13,313
...not just for the plane and the car,
but for today...

246
00:15:13,489 --> 00:15:15,184
...you know, with my father.

247
00:15:15,491 --> 00:15:17,425
You were really understanding.

248
00:15:17,693 --> 00:15:19,684
lt was the least l could do.

249
00:15:19,829 --> 00:15:21,990
Anyway. Good-bye, Mr. Gordon.

250
00:15:22,498 --> 00:15:25,092
lt's in there somewhere. There you go.

251
00:15:47,523 --> 00:15:48,956
lt's my father.

252
00:15:50,560 --> 00:15:52,289
He fought in the war here.

253
00:15:55,765 --> 00:15:58,063
These were his buddies.

254
00:16:08,578 --> 00:16:10,170
Well, you're here.

255
00:16:12,081 --> 00:16:14,174
l brought you here like you wanted.

256
00:16:29,765 --> 00:16:32,563
Thanks for not getting killed
so l could be born.

257
00:16:51,187 --> 00:16:52,779
That was very sweet.

258
00:16:54,190 --> 00:16:56,283
What are you doing here?

259
00:16:56,425 --> 00:16:59,019
Nobody should bury their father alone.

260
00:17:01,931 --> 00:17:02,920
I’m Mickey.

261
00:17:03,599 --> 00:17:04,588
Ellen.

262
00:17:07,870 --> 00:17:09,201
Do you come here often?

263
00:17:24,887 --> 00:17:27,048
You'd have been better off
in the limousine.

264
00:17:27,123 --> 00:17:29,318
I’m much more comfortable here.

265
00:17:32,628 --> 00:17:35,222
l take it you and your father
weren't very close.

266
00:17:36,132 --> 00:17:37,895
No, he left when l was 10.

267
00:17:38,067 --> 00:17:40,729
l'll never forget the last thing he said.

268
00:17:40,903 --> 00:17:42,336
''Get out of my way.''

269
00:17:42,471 --> 00:17:44,234
You can't buy memories like that.

270
00:17:44,307 --> 00:17:45,865
l suppose not.

271
00:17:47,143 --> 00:17:50,909
You'll be at the airport in 90 minutes.
The drive's a breeze.

272
00:17:51,147 --> 00:17:53,138
I’d never say something like that.

273
00:17:53,349 --> 00:17:55,146
- Like what?
- Like, ''lt's a breeze.''

274
00:17:55,351 --> 00:17:58,980
I’m superstitious and that's like begging
for disaster.

275
00:17:59,155 --> 00:18:02,750
lt's like those old war movies.
After the battle they sit around and talk...

276
00:18:02,825 --> 00:18:05,817
...about going home,
and there's a guy named Brooklyn.

277
00:18:05,895 --> 00:18:10,491
''When l get home l'll go to see
my Dodgers, get me a nice hot dog...''

278
00:18:15,438 --> 00:18:16,871
lt always happened, right?

279
00:18:16,939 --> 00:18:20,500
lf ever l get on a small plane
and there's a storm, l never say:

280
00:18:20,643 --> 00:18:22,634
''Piece of cake.''

281
00:18:22,878 --> 00:18:26,143
Never say, ''Famous last words,''
because they could be.

282
00:18:27,617 --> 00:18:29,608
You're a disturbed person, right?

283
00:18:29,885 --> 00:18:32,115
You have no idea.

284
00:18:32,922 --> 00:18:36,517
<i>According to him, he was working hard
all the way back to Paris.</i>

285
00:18:36,826 --> 00:18:40,159
<i>You know those Japanese movies
with dinosaurs in the streets...</i>

286
00:18:41,097 --> 00:18:44,430
...and those people just run out
and wait to get stepped on?

287
00:18:48,704 --> 00:18:52,299
<i>He's got the charm turned up
to warp factor 7...</i>

288
00:18:52,475 --> 00:18:55,911
<i>...and she seems to like him,
but he's not sure.</i>

289
00:18:56,946 --> 00:18:59,540
l never knew that about Wilt Chamberlain.

290
00:18:59,649 --> 00:19:01,879
They say it's true, but you know...

291
00:19:02,051 --> 00:19:05,487
- l had a great time.
- Thank you for everything.

292
00:19:05,655 --> 00:19:07,646
We must stop meeting like this.

293
00:19:12,161 --> 00:19:13,560
Take care of yourself.

294
00:19:15,264 --> 00:19:16,492
Okay.

295
00:19:17,066 --> 00:19:18,465
Have a good flight.

296
00:19:21,837 --> 00:19:23,998
- Can l ask you a question?
- Sure.

297
00:19:24,173 --> 00:19:29,076
- ls this ticket only for this afternoon?
- lt's for any time. Want to change it?

298
00:19:29,245 --> 00:19:31,509
Well, l was thinking... lt's silly.

299
00:19:31,914 --> 00:19:35,042
I’ve never been to Paris.
Maybe l should do some sightseeing.

300
00:19:35,284 --> 00:19:37,184
Sightseeing in Paris?

301
00:19:37,353 --> 00:19:39,344
What a bizarre notion.

302
00:19:40,289 --> 00:19:41,779
What do you got here?

303
00:19:41,924 --> 00:19:44,916
- What do we got here?
- Yeah. You got anything?

304
00:19:45,428 --> 00:19:46,861
We got some stuff.

305
00:19:47,029 --> 00:19:48,860
Like what kind of stuff?

306
00:19:49,198 --> 00:19:51,325
You want to see the Eiffel Tower?

307
00:19:51,600 --> 00:19:53,090
That's here?

308
00:19:56,305 --> 00:19:57,294
See?

309
00:19:57,440 --> 00:19:59,101
You got any other stuff?

310
00:20:08,184 --> 00:20:12,621
<i>He keeps delaying his flight,
buying outfits... He doesn't want to leave.</i>

311
00:20:13,689 --> 00:20:14,883
l find it...

312
00:20:15,057 --> 00:20:17,821
...a lot like New York, but totally different.

313
00:20:24,200 --> 00:20:26,168
<i>Did you always want to be a referee?</i>

314
00:20:26,235 --> 00:20:28,135
<i>No, I started as a player.</i>

315
00:20:28,637 --> 00:20:30,434
<i>- What are you looking at?
- I just--</i>

316
00:20:30,506 --> 00:20:32,497
<i>That I'm vertically challenged?</i>

317
00:20:33,642 --> 00:20:37,976
<i>The best place for me to ref a game is
Madison Square Garden in New York.</i>

318
00:20:38,147 --> 00:20:41,583
<i>Wasn't it a soccer game
where the referee got killed?</i>

319
00:20:41,751 --> 00:20:45,152
<i>- I'm against that.
- Good for you. Take a stand.</i>

320
00:20:45,354 --> 00:20:47,288
<i>You ever get back to the New World?</i>

321
00:20:47,356 --> 00:20:49,847
<i>Every year I visit my father in Wichita.</i>

322
00:20:49,992 --> 00:20:53,587
<i>Wichita? I'll bet his name's Red
and he caps oil-well fires?</i>

323
00:20:53,763 --> 00:20:56,357
<i>No, it's Arthur. And he owned a pet store.</i>

324
00:20:56,499 --> 00:20:57,932
<i>That was my next guess.</i>

325
00:20:58,501 --> 00:21:01,664
<i>- Do you dream in French or English?
- French.</i>

326
00:21:01,871 --> 00:21:03,270
<i>With English subtitles.</i>

327
00:21:03,439 --> 00:21:05,498
<i>I'm impressed. You got little kids...</i>

328
00:21:05,674 --> 00:21:08,643
<i>...2, 3 years old
and they already speak French.</i>

329
00:21:09,779 --> 00:21:13,044
<i>- Rodin never said what he was thinking.
- He's thinking:</i>

330
00:21:13,115 --> 00:21:16,380
<i>''Goddamn, Rodin, three drinks
and I'm nude!''</i>

331
00:21:21,791 --> 00:21:23,190
<i>What can you say?</i>

332
00:21:23,392 --> 00:21:24,689
<i>It was Paris.</i>

333
00:21:31,133 --> 00:21:32,691
You got great stuff.

334
00:21:45,648 --> 00:21:47,309
Got it!

335
00:21:48,651 --> 00:21:50,312
Do you know where we are?

336
00:21:50,486 --> 00:21:52,920
On the Seine. That's the Pont Neuf.

337
00:21:53,556 --> 00:21:56,150
This bridge is in a movie.
Don't you recognize it?

338
00:21:56,492 --> 00:21:58,016
Give me a hint.

339
00:21:59,061 --> 00:22:01,222
''lt's very clear''

340
00:22:01,430 --> 00:22:02,522
Patton.

341
00:22:05,167 --> 00:22:06,566
Patton?

342
00:22:07,503 --> 00:22:11,064
''lt's very clear our love is here to stay''

343
00:22:11,240 --> 00:22:13,504
<i>- An American In Paris?
- Gene Kelly.</i>

344
00:22:13,676 --> 00:22:16,611
Leslie Caron. This is it.
This is very exciting for me.

345
00:22:17,313 --> 00:22:18,712
Come on, sing the rest.

346
00:22:18,948 --> 00:22:21,576
Sing? No, l can't. No.

347
00:22:21,851 --> 00:22:24,945
With my voice the cops will come
with those sirens.

348
00:22:26,722 --> 00:22:28,713
They'll put me in singing jail.

349
00:22:36,198 --> 00:22:37,597
''lt's...

350
00:22:38,567 --> 00:22:41,559
''...very clear...

351
00:22:42,738 --> 00:22:46,299
''...our love is here to stay

352
00:22:48,143 --> 00:22:50,543
''Not for a year...

353
00:22:51,714 --> 00:22:54,274
''...but forever and a day''

354
00:23:03,792 --> 00:23:06,192
Now you'll tell me you're leaving.

355
00:23:09,231 --> 00:23:12,132
The season starts Monday,
and l must get back.

356
00:23:17,139 --> 00:23:20,131
Do you want the afternoon
or the evening flight?

357
00:23:20,910 --> 00:23:23,640
The evening, so we can spend
the day together.

358
00:23:23,812 --> 00:23:25,143
l have to work.

359
00:23:25,314 --> 00:23:27,748
- l'll watch you.
- What?

360
00:23:31,253 --> 00:23:33,312
- This is my place.
- Oh, yeah?

361
00:23:33,656 --> 00:23:34,816
lt's great.

362
00:23:35,024 --> 00:23:38,824
- l had a great time, thanks.
- l had a wonderful time.

363
00:23:39,762 --> 00:23:41,093
So, good night.

364
00:23:41,263 --> 00:23:42,161
Good night.

365
00:23:44,099 --> 00:23:46,329
Would you like to come upstairs?

366
00:23:48,604 --> 00:23:49,571
Really?

367
00:23:50,439 --> 00:23:51,531
Yes.

368
00:23:54,944 --> 00:23:59,847
No. I’m sorry, but to tell you the truth,
l don't find you very attractive.

369
00:24:01,951 --> 00:24:04,545
You've got a big, fat, dumpy ass.

370
00:24:04,853 --> 00:24:07,117
What? He said that?

371
00:24:07,356 --> 00:24:10,416
No, l just said it to see
if you were paying attention.

372
00:24:10,559 --> 00:24:11,787
What he said was:

373
00:24:12,361 --> 00:24:14,192
l would love to.

374
00:24:15,064 --> 00:24:16,088
Come on.

375
00:24:20,970 --> 00:24:22,733
<i>- And they...
- Yeah.</i>

376
00:24:23,205 --> 00:24:25,696
<i>- And it was...
- Oh, yeah.</i>

377
00:24:25,975 --> 00:24:29,968
<i>You know, it was the first time
Mickey never told me anything...</i>

378
00:24:30,145 --> 00:24:33,137
<i>...which meant it was
really something special.</i>

379
00:25:12,454 --> 00:25:14,718
<i>And finally Mickey has to leave.</i>

380
00:25:15,257 --> 00:25:18,021
<i>He left? He actually left?</i>

381
00:25:18,360 --> 00:25:21,022
<i>He had to! The season was starting.</i>

382
00:25:24,533 --> 00:25:25,761
<i>Poor Mickey.</i>

383
00:25:25,934 --> 00:25:29,028
<i>He hadn't had a lot
of beautiful moments in his life.</i>

384
00:25:29,204 --> 00:25:32,139
<i>Even the family dog committed suicide.
He left a note:</i>

385
00:25:32,274 --> 00:25:34,538
<i>''I can't take it anymore, Chi Chi.''</i>

386
00:25:35,644 --> 00:25:39,205
<i>Mickey just never knew that anyone
could be so wonderful.</i>

387
00:25:42,718 --> 00:25:43,980
<i>But he tells himself:</i>

388
00:25:44,053 --> 00:25:47,955
<i>''Forget Paris.
It was just a beautiful few days. Let it go.</i>

389
00:25:48,157 --> 00:25:51,593
<i>''Just let it be a perfect little memory.''</i>

390
00:25:52,394 --> 00:25:53,793
<i>But it's tough.</i>

391
00:26:01,570 --> 00:26:02,628
See this?

392
00:26:03,038 --> 00:26:06,007
They brought Abraham Lincoln
back to life for a few seconds.

393
00:26:06,075 --> 00:26:07,064
When?

394
00:26:08,911 --> 00:26:11,311
Last week they dug him up.

395
00:26:11,747 --> 00:26:16,241
- They gave him this drug, Revivatol.
- No kidding?

396
00:26:16,585 --> 00:26:18,177
lt says he said a few words.

397
00:26:18,320 --> 00:26:20,584
What'd he say? ''How'd the play end?''

398
00:26:22,558 --> 00:26:24,992
How'll you ref with that in your stomach?

399
00:26:25,327 --> 00:26:28,228
You may look like my mother,
but you're not.

400
00:26:30,199 --> 00:26:32,463
- What'll we see today?
- What's playing?

401
00:26:33,202 --> 00:26:36,433
Must we go to the movies?
That's all we ever do.

402
00:26:36,605 --> 00:26:37,936
What do you want to do?

403
00:26:38,707 --> 00:26:41,835
l don't know. l was thinking
maybe we'd go to a...

404
00:26:42,010 --> 00:26:43,102
...museum.

405
00:26:46,348 --> 00:26:48,009
And see what?

406
00:26:50,018 --> 00:26:51,212
Art.

407
00:26:53,622 --> 00:26:54,714
Art.

408
00:26:55,624 --> 00:26:59,116
Tommy, would you like to go
to a museum and see art?

409
00:26:59,361 --> 00:27:00,794
Not today, thank you.

410
00:27:00,963 --> 00:27:04,455
We're in Indianapolis
and you want to see art?

411
00:27:04,633 --> 00:27:07,124
When l was in Paris l saw art, okay?

412
00:27:07,302 --> 00:27:11,238
- l saw the Mona Lisa, l saw stuff.
- With that girl you met?

413
00:27:11,373 --> 00:27:12,305
Ellen.

414
00:27:12,641 --> 00:27:16,634
Let me ask you: Why is she in Paris?
ls she too good to live here?

415
00:27:16,812 --> 00:27:18,404
- Good point.
- What do you mean?

416
00:27:18,480 --> 00:27:22,746
No point. Why don't you shoot
some of that Revivatol into your brains?

417
00:27:22,985 --> 00:27:24,418
l'll go to the museum...

418
00:27:24,486 --> 00:27:26,249
...to see art.

419
00:27:26,388 --> 00:27:28,549
Leave now to avoid the crowds.

420
00:27:28,757 --> 00:27:30,748
Give my regards to Picasso.

421
00:27:31,160 --> 00:27:32,457
Play or call!

422
00:27:35,497 --> 00:27:37,692
Stop looking at me that way, big baby.

423
00:27:38,767 --> 00:27:41,361
Just play the game, okay? How are you?

424
00:27:47,776 --> 00:27:50,836
Walking, walking, right there, right there.

425
00:27:53,115 --> 00:27:54,878
They're all up and down my back.

426
00:27:55,017 --> 00:27:56,712
You're making $5,000,000 a year.

427
00:27:56,785 --> 00:27:59,845
You could be in a submarine bumping
into a periscope. Play ball!

428
00:27:59,922 --> 00:28:02,356
- You got to call that.
- Stop the whining, okay?

429
00:28:02,524 --> 00:28:05,015
One five and a block. Good.

430
00:28:05,360 --> 00:28:07,851
- Are you new in town?
- Make some calls, Mickey.

431
00:28:08,030 --> 00:28:11,022
l'll make them.
I’m getting glare off your head.

432
00:28:12,868 --> 00:28:15,029
No! On the line. On the line.

433
00:28:19,808 --> 00:28:21,207
What, are you tired?

434
00:28:21,877 --> 00:28:25,870
Your girlfriend wore me out last night.
Don't have any legs.

435
00:28:42,331 --> 00:28:43,730
How are you?

436
00:28:46,068 --> 00:28:48,468
lt was a tango. You did the tango.

437
00:28:48,537 --> 00:28:51,131
- Bad call. l was there.
- You weren't.

438
00:28:51,406 --> 00:28:52,338
l was.

439
00:28:52,474 --> 00:28:54,908
- Mick, where'd you buy your clothes?
- Why?

440
00:28:55,077 --> 00:28:57,841
We need to know
where to shop for the kid.

441
00:28:57,980 --> 00:28:59,140
Very funny.

442
00:28:59,348 --> 00:29:02,283
Tell Spike that one. Come on, play ball.

443
00:29:04,586 --> 00:29:05,917
Technical foul.

444
00:29:06,088 --> 00:29:08,579
Foul line. Go to the foul line.

445
00:29:08,857 --> 00:29:10,757
- Quiet!
- Give him a tech.

446
00:29:10,926 --> 00:29:13,360
- Why are you here?
- lt wasn't his play.

447
00:29:14,062 --> 00:29:15,495
Thanks, Spud.

448
00:29:15,664 --> 00:29:16,995
You know something?

449
00:29:17,599 --> 00:29:19,430
You're the only one l can talk to.

450
00:29:19,735 --> 00:29:20,997
Open it up, ready?

451
00:29:21,103 --> 00:29:22,365
<i>What about Ellen?</i>

452
00:29:22,504 --> 00:29:24,438
<i>Do they call each other? Write?</i>

453
00:29:24,606 --> 00:29:26,267
<i>She writes. He calls.</i>

454
00:29:26,441 --> 00:29:28,909
<i>But it's no good. He misses her.</i>

455
00:29:31,113 --> 00:29:34,378
<i>Thanksgiving. Big network game.
Lakers at Detroit.</i>

456
00:29:34,616 --> 00:29:36,846
<i>Kareem Abdul-Jabbar's last season.</i>

457
00:29:37,886 --> 00:29:42,789
<i>They had a celebration in every town
the Lakers played. This time in Detroit.</i>

458
00:29:42,958 --> 00:29:47,190
<i>The biggest rivalry in the league.
They're scalping tickets...</i>

459
00:29:47,396 --> 00:29:51,958
<i>...for $600. Of course, Mickey's crew does
the game because he's the best.</i>

460
00:29:52,134 --> 00:29:57,037
<i>Only it's a holiday, he's thousands of miles
from her, he's miserable.</i>

461
00:29:57,406 --> 00:29:59,704
<i>He's a time bomb.</i>

462
00:30:00,542 --> 00:30:03,033
Wake up and drop dead, you putz!

463
00:30:03,211 --> 00:30:04,644
God, l hate your guts!

464
00:30:04,813 --> 00:30:07,646
Where'd you go to ref school,
Dip Shit Tech?

465
00:30:07,816 --> 00:30:09,647
<i>You pathetic pigs.</i>

466
00:30:09,818 --> 00:30:11,718
That's a foul.

467
00:30:11,920 --> 00:30:14,718
<i>What's the matter,
the Prozac didn't kick in?</i>

468
00:30:14,923 --> 00:30:18,723
Get in the game, you prick.

469
00:30:21,496 --> 00:30:23,487
<i>What a waste of blood.</i>

470
00:30:24,499 --> 00:30:26,467
You suck!

471
00:30:27,336 --> 00:30:31,329
Mickey, how'd you miss that last call?
You want to borrow these?

472
00:30:39,181 --> 00:30:40,808
Let's go, let's play.

473
00:30:41,850 --> 00:30:42,942
Hey, Mickey.

474
00:30:43,085 --> 00:30:46,350
Laimbeer's got me in a headlock.
You waiting for blood?

475
00:30:46,521 --> 00:30:48,682
- Technical foul. Who's shooting?
- For what?

476
00:30:48,757 --> 00:30:50,452
Do you want another one?

477
00:30:50,692 --> 00:30:51,716
What did l say?

478
00:30:51,793 --> 00:30:54,887
Just because you're having a bad game,
don't take it out on me.

479
00:30:54,963 --> 00:30:55,861
You're out!

480
00:30:56,365 --> 00:30:58,356
Are you nuts? lt's my farewell game.

481
00:30:58,533 --> 00:31:01,024
Let me be the first to say farewell.

482
00:31:01,203 --> 00:31:02,693
- Get out of here!
- No.

483
00:31:02,871 --> 00:31:04,202
- You're nuts.
- Really?

484
00:31:04,373 --> 00:31:06,238
- What are you laughing at?
- Nothing.

485
00:31:06,708 --> 00:31:08,369
Technical. For lying.

486
00:31:08,543 --> 00:31:09,976
You out of your mind?

487
00:31:10,112 --> 00:31:11,807
Am l crazy?

488
00:31:11,880 --> 00:31:13,040
