00:45:21,429 --> 00:45:23,090
<i>...an unexpected visitor.</i>

734
00:45:23,264 --> 00:45:25,095
<i>The first husband from Paris?</i>

735
00:45:25,266 --> 00:45:26,597
<i>Close.</i>

736
00:45:29,704 --> 00:45:32,138
<i>A mouse. So she calls an exterminator.</i>

737
00:45:32,473 --> 00:45:36,375
Glue traps. They're not like the old kind
that snap their heads off.

738
00:45:36,444 --> 00:45:40,437
<i>A simple gluey piece of paper.
Put a little food in the middle.</i>

739
00:45:40,615 --> 00:45:44,381
<i>The mouse comes, looks at the food,
goes for the food.</i>

740
00:45:44,552 --> 00:45:48,352
Gets stuck. So he squirms around
but can't get away.

741
00:45:48,623 --> 00:45:50,147
<i>It's how Lucy and I met.</i>

742
00:45:50,391 --> 00:45:52,291
lt's pretty cool.

743
00:45:52,893 --> 00:45:57,125
<i>Coming home the next day,
she hears a commotion in the living room.</i>

744
00:45:57,298 --> 00:46:00,062
<i>Did she get a mouse in the glue?
Don't tell me.</i>

745
00:46:00,167 --> 00:46:01,828
<i>Let me tell this part.</i>

746
00:46:02,136 --> 00:46:04,627
<i>Then you can tell the rest of it.</i>

747
00:46:05,206 --> 00:46:09,802
<i>She'd left the sliding door open
and a pigeon flew in, went after the food...</i>

748
00:46:10,077 --> 00:46:12,739
<i>...and got stuck in the glue.</i>

749
00:46:13,447 --> 00:46:15,415
<i>- She calls the vet.
- Then the vet says:</i>

750
00:46:15,483 --> 00:46:16,780
<i>''Get it right over!''</i>

751
00:46:16,851 --> 00:46:20,582
<i>He's got chemicals that can dissolve
the glue and save the bird.</i>

752
00:46:20,821 --> 00:46:24,188
<i>- She puts the bird in a box, gets in the car.
- And heads for the vet.</i>

753
00:46:24,258 --> 00:46:26,749
<i>- The bird's very nervous.
- Who wouldn't be?</i>

754
00:46:26,927 --> 00:46:28,417
<i>She takes off.</i>

755
00:46:28,763 --> 00:46:31,823
<i>She's driving along,
she hits a huge pothole.</i>

756
00:46:32,500 --> 00:46:34,092
<i>The bird flies into the air...</i>

757
00:46:34,168 --> 00:46:36,932
<i>- ...and sticks to her head.
- You're a liar!</i>

758
00:46:37,104 --> 00:46:38,594
<i>Told you.</i>

759
00:46:39,674 --> 00:46:40,663
Get off.

760
00:46:48,182 --> 00:46:50,116
Help! Help!

761
00:46:51,852 --> 00:46:53,513
Did you see that?

762
00:46:54,021 --> 00:46:56,182
Those are the earrings l wanted.

763
00:47:10,037 --> 00:47:12,801
Mrs. Gordon for Dr. Pilch, please.

764
00:47:13,307 --> 00:47:14,934
Your pet's name?

765
00:47:15,009 --> 00:47:16,977
Get me Dr. Pilch or l'll kill you!

766
00:47:22,683 --> 00:47:24,116
- Honey?
- ln here.

767
00:47:24,452 --> 00:47:26,647
Your lover-man's home.

768
00:47:26,887 --> 00:47:28,320
What a trip l had...

769
00:47:33,260 --> 00:47:34,591
l'll tell her.

770
00:47:35,396 --> 00:47:38,126
Thank you, Doctor. Thanks for calling.
'Bye.

771
00:47:39,133 --> 00:47:42,625
That was the vet. lt's good news.
The pigeon will make it.

772
00:47:45,139 --> 00:47:47,699
Why are you giving me the stink eye?

773
00:47:47,975 --> 00:47:49,909
You had mice in the apartment.

774
00:47:50,044 --> 00:47:52,410
Me? l haven't been here for a month.

775
00:47:52,713 --> 00:47:53,907
l know.

776
00:47:56,917 --> 00:47:59,579
Come on, now. l didn't do anything.

777
00:47:59,720 --> 00:48:03,315
You just had an ''l had
a bird glued to my head'' day.

778
00:48:03,891 --> 00:48:07,418
You go from normal to Tippi Hedren.
lt'd shake a person up.

779
00:48:08,429 --> 00:48:10,021
When do you go away again?

780
00:48:10,231 --> 00:48:11,789
Day after tomorrow.

781
00:48:12,500 --> 00:48:13,831
For how long?

782
00:48:14,068 --> 00:48:15,194
Ten days.

783
00:48:16,070 --> 00:48:18,129
Then I’m home for three. We'll go away.

784
00:48:18,372 --> 00:48:19,270
Great.

785
00:48:20,841 --> 00:48:22,172
Didn't you just...

786
00:48:22,343 --> 00:48:23,537
...finish one?

787
00:48:23,677 --> 00:48:25,872
I’ve gained eight pounds. Okay?

788
00:48:26,013 --> 00:48:28,106
Okay, sure. Fine with me.

789
00:48:28,949 --> 00:48:33,511
ln fact, l think l'll gain 20 more.
Then maybe l'll just be perfect.

790
00:48:33,687 --> 00:48:34,779
How is that?

791
00:48:34,889 --> 00:48:37,551
For me? A dream come true. l can't wait.

792
00:48:37,892 --> 00:48:40,827
Let's go and have a stack
of buttermilk pancakes.

793
00:48:42,062 --> 00:48:43,324
Let's get you big!

794
00:48:43,397 --> 00:48:47,390
Bring your new friends Ben and Jerry.
We'll turn your ass into a helipad.

795
00:48:47,468 --> 00:48:48,696
Come on.

796
00:48:54,775 --> 00:48:56,072
l look terrible.

797
00:48:56,277 --> 00:48:57,539
- No.
- l do.

798
00:48:57,711 --> 00:48:59,770
- You don't.
- l do.

799
00:49:00,915 --> 00:49:02,405
I’m lonely.

800
00:49:04,118 --> 00:49:05,517
l hate my job.

801
00:49:06,053 --> 00:49:10,752
l hate this apartment. l didn't come
all the way from France to be alone.

802
00:49:12,193 --> 00:49:13,125
Lately...

803
00:49:14,061 --> 00:49:17,053
...I’ve been having certain feelings...

804
00:49:17,298 --> 00:49:18,492
...about...

805
00:49:19,133 --> 00:49:20,794
...Safe-T-Man.

806
00:49:25,072 --> 00:49:27,905
Ellen, l love you. l love you so much.

807
00:49:28,075 --> 00:49:32,739
l wish l could do something, but it's
not like l can quit my job or anything.

808
00:49:32,913 --> 00:49:33,937
Why not?

809
00:49:35,583 --> 00:49:36,572
What?

810
00:49:37,351 --> 00:49:39,546
Why can't you quit your job?

811
00:49:40,087 --> 00:49:44,148
Right, that's... That's impossible.
l mean, it's ridiculous.

812
00:49:44,325 --> 00:49:45,724
lt's ridiculous?

813
00:49:46,527 --> 00:49:47,926
l quit my job.

814
00:49:48,095 --> 00:49:50,723
Remember? l gave up everything for you.

815
00:49:56,337 --> 00:49:58,464
Come out on the road again with me.

816
00:49:58,639 --> 00:50:00,470
- We had a great time.
- Great?

817
00:50:00,941 --> 00:50:03,034
Every other day on a different plane?

818
00:50:03,177 --> 00:50:07,944
Room service in the hotel at 1:00 a.m.
while you ice down your knees?

819
00:50:08,115 --> 00:50:09,639
Who wants that life?

820
00:50:11,018 --> 00:50:12,315
l do.

821
00:50:12,953 --> 00:50:14,682
l like my job.

822
00:50:14,955 --> 00:50:17,583
Can't you do it for a local high school?

823
00:50:17,725 --> 00:50:19,784
Those high-school kids are armed.

824
00:50:19,994 --> 00:50:22,155
They pay nothing. Honey, I’m a pro.

825
00:50:22,396 --> 00:50:26,059
I’m one of the best in the league
and it's what I’ve done for ten years.

826
00:50:26,800 --> 00:50:28,062
All right.

827
00:50:28,369 --> 00:50:29,802
I’m sorry.

828
00:50:30,070 --> 00:50:33,062
l know that your job means a lot to you.

829
00:50:33,807 --> 00:50:36,139
l just can't do this anymore.

830
00:50:45,986 --> 00:50:50,787
<i>So he calls me. I once offered him
a job selling cars for his off-season.</i>

831
00:50:50,858 --> 00:50:53,418
<i>He had the personality to do it.</i>

832
00:50:53,827 --> 00:50:54,953
<i>So, he quit?</i>

833
00:50:55,029 --> 00:50:58,692
<i>He asked the league for a year off.
A leave of absence.</i>

834
00:50:59,600 --> 00:51:02,330
<i>He and Ellen are together again.
She talks him...</i>

835
00:51:02,436 --> 00:51:05,633
<i>- ...into buying a little house.
- It was charming.</i>

836
00:51:05,706 --> 00:51:08,470
<i>If ''charming'' means hot and overpriced.</i>

837
00:51:08,642 --> 00:51:11,634
<i>Anyway, she's working out.
She looks fabulous.</i>

838
00:51:11,879 --> 00:51:14,211
<i>Yeah, everything's great...for her.</i>

839
00:51:14,415 --> 00:51:17,077
<i>The knuckleheads at the airlines
finally realize...</i>

840
00:51:17,318 --> 00:51:20,151
<i>...she's 90 times too qualified for her job.</i>

841
00:51:20,521 --> 00:51:24,514
<i>They move her into an office downtown.
She's the head of a department.</i>

842
00:51:24,692 --> 00:51:26,853
<i>She's the happiest she's ever been.</i>

843
00:51:27,027 --> 00:51:28,688
<i>Good! And how's Mickey?</i>

844
00:51:28,862 --> 00:51:31,990
<i>Mickey is not wonderful.</i>

845
00:51:33,634 --> 00:51:35,534
What mileage does it get?

846
00:51:35,703 --> 00:51:38,194
Fabulous. Fabulous mileage.

847
00:51:38,372 --> 00:51:41,136
<i>lt gets 100 in the city
and 3,000 on the highway.</i>

848
00:51:41,275 --> 00:51:43,539
<i>- What?
- Car and Driver called the...</i>

849
00:51:44,645 --> 00:51:46,044
- What are we in?
- Subaru.

850
00:51:46,213 --> 00:51:48,272
Said it was great. Unquote.

851
00:51:49,049 --> 00:51:51,142
You actually knew Michael Jordan?

852
00:51:51,285 --> 00:51:53,651
I’m the one who shaved his head.

853
00:51:55,155 --> 00:51:56,645
<i>So, she's happy...</i>

854
00:51:56,790 --> 00:51:59,224
<i>...he's miserable. And his mind says:</i>

855
00:51:59,293 --> 00:52:02,262
<i>''What the hell is making her so happy?''</i>

856
00:52:03,397 --> 00:52:04,295
Ellen!

857
00:52:05,265 --> 00:52:06,357
Follow that car.

858
00:52:06,433 --> 00:52:09,231
- What?
- The Porsche. Come on, catch up to it.

859
00:52:09,303 --> 00:52:11,498
Come on. Gun this rickshaw!

860
00:52:11,805 --> 00:52:13,739
Move it, that's my wife!

861
00:52:20,581 --> 00:52:21,912
lt's not her.

862
00:52:24,084 --> 00:52:25,312
lt's not her.

863
00:52:25,486 --> 00:52:26,544
lt's not her.

864
00:52:37,331 --> 00:52:38,764
So, you like it?

865
00:52:39,299 --> 00:52:43,292
<i>It wasn't that he couldn't sell cars.
Most days he wasn't bad.</i>

866
00:52:43,437 --> 00:52:44,802
<i>His heart wasn't in it.</i>

867
00:52:45,606 --> 00:52:48,097
<i>The worst was during the playoffs.</i>

868
00:52:49,443 --> 00:52:50,705
<i>Poor Mickey.</i>

869
00:52:50,944 --> 00:52:52,343
<i>That was a rough time.</i>

870
00:52:52,513 --> 00:52:54,504
<i>He made it rough.</i>

871
00:52:54,715 --> 00:52:58,708
Craig gave him a good job.
My brother Richard was dying for that job.

872
00:52:58,852 --> 00:53:00,149
Again with this?

873
00:53:00,854 --> 00:53:02,719
Unlike Mickey...

874
00:53:02,890 --> 00:53:05,017
...Richard would've appreciated that job.

875
00:53:05,225 --> 00:53:07,591
Richard needs instructions to put on a hat.

876
00:53:08,862 --> 00:53:13,299
He fell down some steps when he was
a baby. Can we get back to the point?

877
00:53:13,467 --> 00:53:17,028
You're giving her the wrong idea.
You're making Ellen the villain.

878
00:53:17,237 --> 00:53:18,966
There's two sides to everything.

879
00:53:19,039 --> 00:53:20,199
You tell it.

880
00:53:20,474 --> 00:53:21,941
Ellen would talk to me...

881
00:53:22,009 --> 00:53:23,340
<i>...during that period.</i>

882
00:53:23,544 --> 00:53:25,478
- Veal parmigiana.
- What?

883
00:53:25,646 --> 00:53:28,877
That's the only thing
he'll eat at a restaurant.

884
00:53:29,049 --> 00:53:30,983
We've been out with him, l know.

885
00:53:31,151 --> 00:53:34,780
There's so many things he'll only do.
He'll only go to the movies.

886
00:53:34,888 --> 00:53:37,880
''What'll we do tonight?''
''Let's go to a movie.''

887
00:53:38,092 --> 00:53:39,320
He's used to that.

888
00:53:39,426 --> 00:53:42,862
ln Paris, he went to the museum
and to the ballet.

889
00:53:43,163 --> 00:53:47,395
Forget Paris. He was courting.
They'll do anything when they're courting.

890
00:53:47,568 --> 00:53:49,559
Craig knitted me a sweater.

891
00:53:50,003 --> 00:53:52,904
<i>We went to the theatre
to see Phantom of the Opera.</i>

892
00:53:53,073 --> 00:53:55,769
- Oh, that's so beautiful.
- Yeah.

893
00:53:55,909 --> 00:53:57,399
You know what Mickey said?

894
00:53:57,578 --> 00:54:00,911
- You liked it?
- l loved it. lt was romantic.

895
00:54:01,415 --> 00:54:04,282
The guy's got broken dinnerware
on his face...

896
00:54:04,418 --> 00:54:07,353
...under which is a pizza,
and she's in love with him?

897
00:54:07,521 --> 00:54:09,455
She was in love with his soul.

898
00:54:09,523 --> 00:54:12,185
<i>That's ridiculous.
lt's like Beauty and the Beast.</i>

899
00:54:12,359 --> 00:54:14,350
lt's all stuff they sell to women.

900
00:54:14,528 --> 00:54:17,588
Teddy Stein was the sweetest guy
in my high school.

901
00:54:17,798 --> 00:54:22,167
He had a bit of a droopy eye and a mole
on his cheek. Could not get a date.

902
00:54:22,269 --> 00:54:24,999
But this Phantom with an exploded head...

903
00:54:25,139 --> 00:54:27,733
Women are squirming in their seats.
lt's not real.

904
00:54:27,808 --> 00:54:29,366
l loved it. The music--

905
00:54:29,543 --> 00:54:33,035
<i>You know what the big song was?
lt was School Days.</i>

906
00:54:33,814 --> 00:54:35,213
- What?
- Yeah!

907
00:54:38,385 --> 00:54:40,876
''School days, school days
Dear old...

908
00:54:40,954 --> 00:54:43,582
''...golden rule days''
Do they think we're dopes?

909
00:54:45,559 --> 00:54:47,322
You hated the whole evening?

910
00:54:47,394 --> 00:54:50,158
No, no. The veal parmigiana was good.

911
00:54:50,731 --> 00:54:52,722
<i>It was a hard time for him.</i>

912
00:54:52,800 --> 00:54:54,097
<i>He was unhappy...</i>

913
00:54:54,168 --> 00:54:56,102
...so everything irritated him.

914
00:54:56,470 --> 00:54:59,962
l guess. She was irritating him
and he was irritating her.

915
00:55:00,140 --> 00:55:01,903
They irritated each other.

916
00:55:01,975 --> 00:55:04,307
- Things were horrible.
- Then they got worse.

917
00:55:04,578 --> 00:55:06,409
- What do you mean?
- The father.

918
00:55:06,914 --> 00:55:09,747
- l forgot about the father!
- The father's dead.

919
00:55:09,883 --> 00:55:12,545
- They buried him in France.
- No, Ellen's father.

920
00:55:12,753 --> 00:55:14,414
Why didn't you say?

921
00:55:14,588 --> 00:55:17,352
More Perrier, please.
This was a nightmare.

922
00:55:17,491 --> 00:55:19,584
- Why?
- He retired. He was a widower.

923
00:55:19,927 --> 00:55:22,862
And he also had
a few little health problems.

924
00:55:23,130 --> 00:55:25,462
The wrestling brothers didn't want
to take him.

925
00:55:25,532 --> 00:55:28,399
- So he moves in with them.
- Ellen's working days.

926
00:55:28,502 --> 00:55:31,027
Mickey is working a lot of nights.

927
00:55:31,271 --> 00:55:34,672
Mickey's home a lot
with Ellen's dad, Arthur.

928
00:55:35,008 --> 00:55:39,809
Arthur is the kind of guy
who could drive you insane.

929
00:55:40,214 --> 00:55:41,203
How?

930
00:55:41,381 --> 00:55:43,372
''You asked for it...

931
00:55:43,717 --> 00:55:45,412
''...you got it...

932
00:55:46,386 --> 00:55:48,013
''...Toyota.

933
00:55:51,525 --> 00:55:53,891
''You asked for it...

934
00:55:54,061 --> 00:55:55,551
''...you got it...

935
00:55:56,930 --> 00:55:58,659
''...Toyota.''

936
00:56:52,019 --> 00:56:54,749
''Ed's Tropical Aquarium.''

937
00:56:56,089 --> 00:56:57,317
''Mattress City.''

938
00:56:58,258 --> 00:57:00,852
''Donuts, Donuts, Donuts.''

939
00:57:02,262 --> 00:57:05,026
''Mister Sid's Tuxedos.''

940
00:57:05,766 --> 00:57:07,700
''Six Guys from Greece...

941
00:57:07,901 --> 00:57:10,563
''...Authentic Greek Food.''

942
00:57:15,275 --> 00:57:17,368
Why don't you tell him to stop?

943
00:57:17,544 --> 00:57:20,035
l don't think he knows he's doing it.

944
00:57:20,213 --> 00:57:22,010
So this is your life now?

945
00:57:22,149 --> 00:57:24,140
How did you let this happen to you?

946
00:57:24,484 --> 00:57:25,883
l don't know.

947
00:57:26,119 --> 00:57:29,054
The longest l lived with anybody
before this was...

948
00:57:29,189 --> 00:57:30,622
...eight hours, you know.

949
00:57:30,691 --> 00:57:32,454
That made me feel stifled.

950
00:57:32,726 --> 00:57:34,853
I’m just not used to...

951
00:57:34,995 --> 00:57:37,987
...someone else having an opinion
about my life.

952
00:57:38,231 --> 00:57:40,096
An opinion l have to listen to.

953
00:57:40,167 --> 00:57:41,600
No, you don't.

954
00:57:41,902 --> 00:57:43,494
- l don't?
- No.

955
00:57:44,304 --> 00:57:45,794
So, what are you saying?

956
00:57:45,906 --> 00:57:50,104
A wife is somebody to adore you
and have sex with and not bother you?

957
00:57:50,410 --> 00:57:51,741
Keep going.

958
00:57:52,012 --> 00:57:53,138
What?

959
00:57:53,413 --> 00:57:55,574
Chef of the Future, what's with the meat?

960
00:57:55,649 --> 00:57:57,139
Making progress?

961
00:57:57,751 --> 00:57:59,241
lt's not quite there yet.

962
00:57:59,419 --> 00:58:01,751
You want to give me a time frame?

963
00:58:01,822 --> 00:58:04,154
Maybe early next week, the fall,
Christmas?

964
00:58:04,324 --> 00:58:06,315
So we can plan our vacation.

965
00:58:06,526 --> 00:58:09,017
lt's just this short of greatness.

966
00:58:09,296 --> 00:58:11,161
So are you, Jack.

967
00:58:11,331 --> 00:58:13,595
She got you. lt's a good one.

968
00:58:13,767 --> 00:58:16,258
Go! Make the girl food. The salad.

969
00:58:16,436 --> 00:58:20,236
Oh, Ellen, let's go make the girl food.
The salad.

970
00:58:22,442 --> 00:58:25,775
The same thing happened to me
when l first got married.

971
00:58:25,946 --> 00:58:29,643
''How can you always leave me?
l didn't get married to be alone.''

972
00:58:29,716 --> 00:58:33,618
She said, ''Give it up.
Stay home, get a real job.''

973
00:58:33,854 --> 00:58:38,382
l said, ''You're asking me to give up
what l do, what l am. l can't do it.''

974
00:58:38,458 --> 00:58:39,652
She understood?

975
00:58:39,993 --> 00:58:41,984
We worked out a compromise.

976
00:58:42,195 --> 00:58:44,459
l went back to work and she divorced me.

977
00:58:45,399 --> 00:58:46,366
Lois?

978
00:58:47,067 --> 00:58:49,900
No, this was Beverly, the first Mrs. Jack.

979
00:58:50,804 --> 00:58:52,169
l didn't know about her.

980
00:58:52,239 --> 00:58:54,366
Then l met Lois and she got it.

981
00:58:55,275 --> 00:58:56,367
Got what?

982
00:58:57,778 --> 00:59:02,181
Mickey, l don't like to stick my nose
into anybody's business...

983
00:59:02,315 --> 00:59:03,805
- But...
- But...

984
00:59:04,084 --> 00:59:08,987
lf you're with a woman and she doesn't get
what you are, what's in your guts...

985
00:59:10,657 --> 00:59:11,851
...move on.

986
00:59:12,392 --> 00:59:13,882
Move on?

987
00:59:14,227 --> 00:59:15,956
Move on.

988
00:59:16,830 --> 00:59:18,388
Jack, what are you saying?

989
00:59:20,100 --> 00:59:21,829
I’m saying move on.

990
00:59:27,007 --> 00:59:28,497
You're up.

991
00:59:29,643 --> 00:59:31,611
l must get going.

992
00:59:31,711 --> 00:59:32,973
You look nice.

993
00:59:33,180 --> 00:59:34,340
Thanks.

994
00:59:35,115 --> 00:59:38,778
Could l talk to you before you go?
l hardly get to see you anymore.

995
00:59:39,853 --> 00:59:41,252
Sure. What is it?

996
00:59:41,555 --> 00:59:46,458
- l just wanted to tell you...
- ''You asked for it, you got it, Toyota.''

997
00:59:47,394 --> 00:59:48,520
'Morning, Pop.

998
00:59:52,799 --> 00:59:54,061
''Non-Dairy...

999
00:59:54,734 --> 00:59:55,792
''...Creamer.''

1000
01:00:04,344 --> 01:00:06,107
''You asked for it...''

1001
01:00:07,380 --> 01:00:08,642
What's going on?

1002
01:00:13,653 --> 01:00:15,746
I’m going back to refereeing.

1003
01:00:23,864 --> 01:00:26,856
l told the league that l want
to go back to work.

1004
01:00:28,535 --> 01:00:31,993
You saw that l tried,
but l just can't do this anymore.

1005
01:00:32,239 --> 01:00:34,332
l can't sit here with him all day.

1006
01:00:34,741 --> 01:00:38,643
When you said he'd live with us,
you gave no clue what shape he was in.

1007
01:00:38,712 --> 01:00:39,940
Honey, he's sick.

1008
01:00:40,614 --> 01:00:41,808
What can l do?

1009
01:00:42,282 --> 01:00:46,343
Take him to work. He can wander
around the airport muttering.

1010
01:00:47,287 --> 01:00:49,414
Thousands of people do that.

1011
01:00:55,495 --> 01:00:58,191
lf he wasn't here everything'd be fine?

1012
01:01:01,101 --> 01:01:03,092
Ellen, l like being a referee.

1013
01:01:03,270 --> 01:01:08,173
l love being a referee. lt's a big part
of who l am and I’m starting to miss me.

1014
01:01:08,241 --> 01:01:10,141
And me is the guy you married.

1015
01:01:10,744 --> 01:01:12,905
When did you decide to do this?

1016
01:01:13,380 --> 01:01:15,143
l thought about it for two weeks.

1017
01:01:17,017 --> 01:01:21,420
Did it ever occur to you to talk to me
about it? To see what l thought?

1018
01:01:21,721 --> 01:01:23,814
l already knew what you thought.

1019
01:01:24,925 --> 01:01:26,984
But you're doing it anyway.

1020
01:01:30,230 --> 01:01:34,189
l must do this. lt's important to us.
l want to love you, not resent you.

1021
01:01:35,769 --> 01:01:37,327
You resent me?

1022
01:01:38,038 --> 01:01:42,600
'Cause when you were unhappy, l cared.
Now I’m unhappy and you don't care.

1023
01:01:42,742 --> 01:01:46,303
l just found out.
l haven't had time not to care.

1024
01:01:46,379 --> 01:01:47,573
You didn't notice?

1025
01:01:47,647 --> 01:01:51,674
Yesterday l ran out of toothpaste
and l burst into tears. ls that normal?

1026
01:01:51,818 --> 01:01:55,686
We never have sex anymore.
Has that even caught your attention?

1027
01:01:56,356 --> 01:02:00,725
We're on different schedules.
When you come home I’m asleep already.

1028
01:02:00,894 --> 01:02:02,088
When l come home--

1029
01:02:02,262 --> 01:02:06,255
We used to do it 19 times a day
in every room in the house.

1030
01:02:06,499 --> 01:02:10,435
lf the Kramers weren't home next door,
we used their place.

1031
01:02:10,770 --> 01:02:14,069
Two times. Two times you wanted
to have sex and l didn't.

1032
01:02:14,140 --> 01:02:17,701
Fifty times, l wanted to and you didn't.
Two times l asked.

1033
01:02:17,844 --> 01:02:20,404
So it's my fault? Why didn't you ask?

1034
01:02:20,780 --> 01:02:24,181
When you show no interest?
l feel like I’m begging.

1035
01:02:24,384 --> 01:02:27,012
What about when you're not interested?

1036
01:02:27,087 --> 01:02:28,418
When did that happen?

1037
01:02:28,555 --> 01:02:30,284
Last week. ln the morning.

1038
01:02:30,590 --> 01:02:32,455
Remember? l started to...

1039
01:02:32,892 --> 01:02:36,453
...do that thing you used to like.
You said, ''Get off me. What is that?''

1040
01:02:36,529 --> 01:02:40,829
<i>lt was 6:30 a.m.! That wasn't love.
You were slipping me into your schedule.</i>

1041
01:02:40,900 --> 01:02:43,300
Fine, if that's the way you see it...

1042
01:02:46,539 --> 01:02:48,097
Oh, Mickey.

1043
01:02:48,375 --> 01:02:52,311
l have a vacation coming up,
so why don't we go away?

1044
01:02:52,412 --> 01:02:54,505
We could go to Santa Barbara.

1045
01:02:55,448 --> 01:02:56,938
I’m leaving Monday.

1046
01:03:08,094 --> 01:03:10,790
How many more years will you do this?

1047
01:03:11,097 --> 01:03:12,189
What? Referee?

1048
01:03:12,265 --> 01:03:13,254
Yes.

1049
01:03:14,334 --> 01:03:15,631
l don't know.

1050
01:03:17,637 --> 01:03:20,333
Well, give me a clue. One?

1051
01:03:20,473 --> 01:03:22,236
Ten? Fifteen?

1052
01:03:23,576 --> 01:03:24,907
l don't know.

1053
01:03:27,914 --> 01:03:29,176
l got to go.

1054
01:03:55,775 --> 01:03:57,106
<i>He just left her?</i>

1055
01:03:57,277 --> 01:03:58,767
<i>Can you believe that?</i>

1056
01:03:58,945 --> 01:04:01,539
<i>- He didn't leave. He went back to work.
- Exactly.</i>

1057
01:04:01,748 --> 01:04:04,376
So his job was more important
than his wife.

1058
01:04:04,684 --> 01:04:09,451
Both were. Marriage can't work with
one person happy and the other miserable.

1059
01:04:09,522 --> 01:04:12,889
Marriage is both people being
equally miserable.

1060
01:04:14,427 --> 01:04:15,587
What?

1061
01:04:16,196 --> 01:04:17,686
No, l was just--

1062
01:04:18,298 --> 01:04:21,893
What if l lost my column
and l had to go back on the road?

1063
01:04:22,535 --> 01:04:23,797
Could that happen?

1064
01:04:23,937 --> 01:04:27,270
Of course. Papers fold, merge,
you get a new editor...

1065
01:04:27,640 --> 01:04:29,130
You never mentioned this.

1066
01:04:29,809 --> 01:04:31,777
Would it have made a difference?

1067
01:04:32,345 --> 01:04:34,745
Well, no. Not really.

1068
01:04:34,914 --> 01:04:38,042
Not really? That's a real crowd-pleaser.

1069
01:04:40,019 --> 01:04:43,853
Sure, it would make some difference.
How could it not?

1070
01:04:44,657 --> 01:04:46,488
We're getting married Sunday.

1071
01:04:46,559 --> 01:04:50,325
I’d like to know if I’m getting the first
or second Mrs. Jack.

1072
01:04:51,297 --> 01:04:56,200
Any man who refers to his wives
as ''Mrs. Jack'' is an idiot.

1073
01:04:56,503 --> 01:04:59,063
Any man who repeats it is a bigger idiot.

1074
01:05:02,008 --> 01:05:02,997
l'll...

1075
01:05:06,613 --> 01:05:09,776
- I’d better...
- Nah. Sit down, relax.

1076
01:05:10,517 --> 01:05:14,681
Lucy'll fix it. She's the Bob Vila
of relationships.

1077
01:05:15,355 --> 01:05:17,323
You're hungry, have some bread.

1078
01:05:17,524 --> 01:05:19,754
Everything'll look better after bread.

1079
01:05:19,959 --> 01:05:22,951
Why did l start anything?
Why did l say that?

1080
01:05:25,865 --> 01:05:28,095
This is good. ls there butter?

1081
01:05:29,702 --> 01:05:33,263
- lt's nothing, just pre-wedding jitters.
- You think?

1082
01:05:33,473 --> 01:05:37,034
You kidding? The week l got married
l threw up every day.

1083
01:05:37,377 --> 01:05:39,902
- Her mother was poisoning me, but--
- Stop.

1084
01:05:39,979 --> 01:05:41,537
Will you just stop?

1085
01:05:42,715 --> 01:05:44,376
Oh, l think I’m scared.

1086
01:05:44,551 --> 01:05:45,779
Of what?

1087
01:05:46,052 --> 01:05:49,488
That l parked too far from the curb.
What do you mean?

1088
01:05:49,622 --> 01:05:53,888
I’ve been single for 40 years
and I’m getting married Sunday. Oh, God!

1089
01:05:54,961 --> 01:05:56,394
Come on.

1090
01:05:56,463 --> 01:05:59,057
Take it easy. You're all right.

1091
01:05:59,232 --> 01:06:01,325
Why did l say that to him?

1092
01:06:01,468 --> 01:06:03,459
l didn't mean that.

1093
01:06:03,837 --> 01:06:06,135
Maybe I’m too scared to get married.

1094
01:06:06,272 --> 01:06:11,209
Oh, listen to me. l lost 15 pounds
for this wedding. You're getting married.

1095
01:06:12,679 --> 01:06:17,173
You shouldn't listen to Ellen and Mickey
stories before you get married.

1096
01:06:17,250 --> 01:06:20,913
lt's like watching a horror movie
before you go to bed.

1097
01:06:22,388 --> 01:06:25,118
Don't you think Mickey was wrong
and Ellen was right?

1098
01:06:25,258 --> 01:06:26,748
Of course.

1099
01:06:27,360 --> 01:06:30,852
Also Ellen was wrong
and Mickey was right.

1100
01:06:31,164 --> 01:06:34,361
See, their marriage had
one overriding problem.

1101
01:06:34,634 --> 01:06:36,534
One was a man and one was a woman.

1102
01:06:38,638 --> 01:06:40,037
So what happened?

1103
01:06:40,340 --> 01:06:41,466
Did they break up?

1104
01:06:41,741 --> 01:06:43,538
lt was kind of hard to tell.

1105
01:06:43,676 --> 01:06:46,941
Were they separated because
he happened to be away...

1106
01:06:47,113 --> 01:06:51,743
<i>...or were they separated because
they were, you know, separated?</i>

1107
01:06:52,619 --> 01:06:54,780
Maybe l got married too fast.

1108
01:06:54,954 --> 01:06:58,014
No, there's no such thing
as too fast or too slow.

1109
01:06:58,191 --> 01:06:59,658
lt's whenever it's right.

1110
01:06:59,959 --> 01:07:01,950
Although you moved a little fast.

1111
01:07:02,962 --> 01:07:06,955
lt's just that when my first marriage ended
l felt so lost.

1112
01:07:07,400 --> 01:07:10,460
l wasn't looking for anyone,
but then he came along.

1113
01:07:10,637 --> 01:07:11,797
Mickey.

1114
01:07:12,205 --> 01:07:15,038
He was so different from the others.
He was cute.

1115
01:07:15,308 --> 01:07:20,211
He's adorable. Every time l see him,
l want to pick him up and give him a hug.

1116
01:07:22,148 --> 01:07:25,549
The other ones were very polished.
Stylish.

1117
01:07:26,653 --> 01:07:29,315
Then this little referee shows up.

1118
01:07:29,489 --> 01:07:30,979
He made me laugh.

1119
01:07:31,157 --> 01:07:34,183
He put me on a pedestal.
He made me feel loved.

1120
01:07:34,727 --> 01:07:37,218
As only a little referee can.

1121
01:07:37,997 --> 01:07:40,659
Just what l needed to get me through that.

1122
01:07:42,168 --> 01:07:43,430
Oh, God.

1123
01:07:43,570 --> 01:07:44,559
What?

1124
01:07:44,737 --> 01:07:47,672
Do you think l married Mickey
on the rebound?

1125
01:07:50,577 --> 01:07:51,601
What's funny?

1126
01:07:52,245 --> 01:07:53,075
Get it?

1127
01:07:53,179 --> 01:07:55,511
Rebound. He's a basketball referee.

1128
01:07:58,851 --> 01:08:00,682
Keep your seats, kids.

1129
01:08:01,187 --> 01:08:05,248
- You know the difference between us?
- You still enjoy your mother bathing you?

1130
01:08:05,391 --> 01:08:10,886
No, the difference is you're a dope
and I’m not. l say it with great affection.

1131
01:08:10,964 --> 01:08:12,454
- I’m a dope?
- Craig?

1132
01:08:12,532 --> 01:08:13,692
Big dope.

1133
01:08:13,866 --> 01:08:15,959
We're both the same. We're rigid.

1134
01:08:16,102 --> 01:08:17,364
I’m not rigid.

1135
01:08:17,537 --> 01:08:19,528
- Craig?
- You're an ironing board.

1136
01:08:19,706 --> 01:08:23,699
That's not true. Please!
Come on, guys, l change.

1137
01:08:23,776 --> 01:08:24,765
- Tuna rye.
- Me.

1138
01:08:24,844 --> 01:08:25,936
- Tuna wheat.
- Me.

1139
01:08:26,012 --> 01:08:27,946
- Veal parmesan sandwich?
- Him.

1140
01:08:28,047 --> 01:08:31,539
See? l know what l am,
so l don't get married.

1141
01:08:31,718 --> 01:08:35,119
Would a woman let me spend $1,400
on old baseball cards?

1142
01:08:35,288 --> 01:08:36,983
Forget it.

1143
01:08:37,123 --> 01:08:38,784
But you married this woman.

1144
01:08:38,992 --> 01:08:43,725
And you seem upset that your life
isn't exactly the same as it was before.

1145
01:08:45,665 --> 01:08:46,927
lt isn't.

1146
01:08:47,800 --> 01:08:49,290
You're married...

1147
01:08:50,069 --> 01:08:51,297
...and you're up.

1148
01:08:58,011 --> 01:08:59,501
When he travels...

1149
01:08:59,679 --> 01:09:03,775
...not only am l lonely,
l don't even know who l am by myself.

1150
01:09:04,517 --> 01:09:05,745
You don't?

1151
01:09:07,820 --> 01:09:09,651
Like when you're with a guy...

1152
01:09:09,822 --> 01:09:13,918
...not just for a night, but really
with a husband or a boyfriend...

1153
01:09:14,694 --> 01:09:19,757
...and you keep re-inventing yourself to be
the perfect woman for that relationship.

1154
01:09:19,966 --> 01:09:21,297
Yeah, right.

1155
01:09:21,701 --> 01:09:22,599
Right.

1156
01:09:24,437 --> 01:09:25,665
l don't know...

1157
01:09:26,139 --> 01:09:29,040
lf l took time before or between...

1158
01:09:29,475 --> 01:09:33,275
...you know, to find out who l really am,
by myself...

1159
01:09:33,346 --> 01:09:36,338
...who l could be, you know,
without any guy around...

1160
01:09:38,184 --> 01:09:40,448
l know I’m in here somewhere.

1161
01:09:40,920 --> 01:09:44,219
l can hear myself screaming
from a distance.

1162
01:09:44,691 --> 01:09:46,750
Does Mickey know you feel this way?

1163
01:09:49,362 --> 01:09:53,196
l don't think Mickey would understand it
in the right way.

1164
01:09:53,466 --> 01:09:55,525
<i>Things just weren't comfortable anymore.</i>

1165
01:09:55,702 --> 01:09:59,331
<i>For either of them.
They were pretending to be married.</i>

1166
01:09:59,739 --> 01:10:03,334
<i>It was sad, because they were married
and they we're both very lonely.</i>

1167
01:10:03,976 --> 01:10:05,466
<i>Oh, gee.</i>

1168
01:10:05,978 --> 01:10:08,640
''Brushless Car Wash.''

1169
01:10:11,484 --> 01:10:13,975
''Mario's Pizza Town.''

1170
01:10:17,090 --> 01:10:18,717
''Laundry World.''

1171
01:10:21,494 --> 01:10:23,155
<i>They decided to get help.</i>

1172
01:10:23,229 --> 01:10:25,026
<i>They went to a marriage counsellor.</i>

1173
01:10:25,098 --> 01:10:27,191
Let me explain my philosophy.

1174
01:10:27,600 --> 01:10:31,400
l see marriage simply
as a form of legalized rape.

1175
01:10:31,537 --> 01:10:34,768
<i>Mickey thought they should see
someone else. Drs. Don and Debbie.</i>

1176
01:10:34,841 --> 01:10:37,708
l don't understand. lf you miss me,
why aren't you happy...

1177
01:10:37,777 --> 01:10:39,039
...when l come home?

1178
01:10:39,378 --> 01:10:41,209
Because l know you'll leave again.

1179
01:10:41,280 --> 01:10:44,477
That's logical. l'll leave,
so let's not have fun while I’m home?

1180
01:10:44,550 --> 01:10:45,642
Now it's my fault?

1181
01:10:46,719 --> 01:10:49,415
When l come home I’m excited to see you.

1182
01:10:49,589 --> 01:10:50,783
You're not excited.

1183
01:10:50,957 --> 01:10:54,393
- You're horny.
- ls that bad? ls that such a bad thing?

1184
01:10:55,128 --> 01:10:57,858
When do you two get involved?
When there's gunplay?

1185
01:11:03,803 --> 01:11:07,466
l just want it to always be like
that week in Paris.

1186
01:11:07,874 --> 01:11:09,865
lt can't be like that, Mickey.

1187
01:11:11,110 --> 01:11:12,338
l know.

1188
01:11:12,512 --> 01:11:15,276
<i>So, finally,
things weren't getting any better.</i>

1189
01:11:15,381 --> 01:11:18,009
<i>So, Ellen did what she had to do.</i>

1190
01:12:17,210 --> 01:12:19,201
Hi, you're back already.

1191
01:12:20,847 --> 01:12:22,075
Where were you?

1192
01:12:22,582 --> 01:12:24,550
Wichita. l left you a note.

1193
01:12:25,284 --> 01:12:28,117
Yeah. Well, l just got here.

1194
01:12:31,824 --> 01:12:32,882
Where's your dad?

1195
01:12:33,626 --> 01:12:34,957
Wichita.

1196
01:12:37,230 --> 01:12:38,629
What's he doing there?

1197
01:12:39,966 --> 01:12:41,957
l left him with my brothers.

1198
01:12:43,035 --> 01:12:44,730
- Really?
- Oh, Mickey...

1199
01:12:44,871 --> 01:12:46,498
l want this to work.

1200
01:12:48,374 --> 01:12:49,864
l love you.

1201
01:12:56,749 --> 01:12:59,343
Honey, I’m sorry. l didn't mean anything.

1202
01:12:59,418 --> 01:13:00,646
Me too.

1203
01:13:01,053 --> 01:13:05,513
l was crying about Mickey and Ellen.
lt's so sweet the way she came back.

1204
01:13:05,892 --> 01:13:08,019
Why do all your women end up crying?

1205
01:13:08,094 --> 01:13:09,391
She's not...

1206
01:13:09,829 --> 01:13:13,765
- This is Jack Garrett. The referee.
- Very nice to meet you.

1207
01:13:13,900 --> 01:13:15,629
I’ve heard a lot about you.

1208
01:13:17,270 --> 01:13:19,670
l was the ''As told to'' on Jack's book.

1209
01:13:19,839 --> 01:13:22,171
And this is Mrs. Jack.

1210
01:13:23,776 --> 01:13:24,936
Lois. Hi.

1211
01:13:25,011 --> 01:13:26,603
lt's very nice to meet you.

1212
01:13:26,746 --> 01:13:28,737
Congratulations. Let's eat.

1213
01:13:29,081 --> 01:13:31,413
- Craig. Lucy.
- Hi, nice to meet you.

1214
01:13:32,084 --> 01:13:33,176
Good to meet you.

1215
01:13:33,352 --> 01:13:34,284
Craig.

